I have an idea for how to implement our own SOC calculation. In fact, I already use it in one project 🙂 so we will use that concept.

At the same time, for purely selfless reasons, I would like to have my own signature in the project, so we will call this value SOCHavrla and interpret it that way on the web interface.

My idea is that the first prerequisite we need to implement is the calculation of the pack’s internal resistance.

We will do it like this:

Every 50 ms, we will store the current and voltage values.

Every 100 ms, we will calculate:

R = ΔV / ΔI

In my own project, I have implemented it like this:

    /* ================= R0 odhad na 100 ms tik =================
       Detekce skoku proudu a výpočet R = ΔV/ΔI po krátké prodlevě.
       Vstupy bereme z 50ms snapshotů (last*_50ms), ale logiku děláme zde (100ms).
    */
    int16_t I_now = last_current_dA_50ms;
    uint16_t V_now = last_volts_dV_50ms;

    // Cooldown
    if (rstep_cooldown_ticks_100ms > 0) {
        rstep_cooldown_ticks_100ms--;
    }

    // Detekce skoku (BEFORE = minulý 100ms snapshot)
    int16_t dI = (int16_t)(I_now - prev_I_100ms_dA);
    if (!rstep_armed_100ms &&
        (dI >= RSTEP_MIN_DELTA_I_dA || dI <= -RSTEP_MIN_DELTA_I_dA) &&
        rstep_cooldown_ticks_100ms == 0) {
        rstep_I_before_dA = prev_I_100ms_dA;
        rstep_V_before_dV = prev_V_100ms_dV;
        rstep_post_delay_ticks_100ms = RSTEP_POST_DELAY_TICKS_100ms;  // počkáme ~100 ms
        rstep_armed_100ms = 1;
    }

    // AFTER po krátké prodlevě: vyhodnoť ΔV/ΔI a filtruj
    if (rstep_armed_100ms) {
        if (rstep_post_delay_ticks_100ms > 0) {
            rstep_post_delay_ticks_100ms--;
        } else {
            int16_t I_after_dA = I_now;
            uint16_t V_after_dV = V_now; 
int16_t dI2 = (int16_t)(I_after_dA - rstep_I_before_dA);
            if (dI2 >= RSTEP_MIN_DELTA_I_dA || dI2 <= -RSTEP_MIN_DELTA_I_dA) {
                // ΔV v dV -> µV (0.1 V = 100000 µV)
                int32_t dV_uV = ((int32_t)V_after_dV - (int32_t)rstep_V_before_dV) * 100000;
                if (dV_uV < 0) dV_uV = -dV_uV;
                int32_t dI_abs = (dI2 < 0) ? -dI2 : dI2;
                if (dI_abs > 0) {
                    int32_t R_sample = dV_uV / dI_abs; // µV per dA
                    // Guard: rozumné napěťové okno packu
                    if (sme_volts_dV >= 2700u && sme_volts_dV <= 4300u &&
                        R_sample >= R_OHMS_MIN_uV_PER_dA && R_sample <= R_OHMS_MAX_uV_PER_dA) {
                        if (!r_est_inited) {
                            r_est_ewma_uV_per_dA = R_sample;
                            r_est_inited = 1;
                        } else {
                            r_est_ewma_uV_per_dA =
                                ((R_EST_EWMA_DEN - R_EST_EWMA_NUM) * r_est_ewma_uV_per_dA +
                                  R_EST_EWMA_NUM * R_sample) / R_EST_EWMA_DEN;
                        }
                        run_PACK_R_uV_PER_dA = r_est_ewma_uV_per_dA;
                    }
                }
            }
            // cooldown ~2 s a odjištění
            rstep_cooldown_ticks_100ms = RSTEP_COOLDOWN_TICKS_100ms;
            rstep_armed_100ms = 0;
        }
    }

    // posuň 100ms „previous“
    prev_I_100ms_dA = I_now;
    prev_V_100ms_dV = V_now;







This result will be displayed on the web in the “More info” section, for example as R_mibha, and we will verify whether it really measures the actual internal resistance of the battery.

In my project, on the car, the 180 Ah battery has about 60 mΩ, and the 60 Ah battery has about 120 mΩ.

It is possible that the inverters cannot create a large enough current change within 100 ms, but I believe they can.
We will set the default value to 80 mΩ.
Why are we doing this?

I will provide you with 3 tables (60/94/120) where cell voltage is mapped to SOC.

However, because the cell voltage changes depending on the current, we can use the known internal resistance of the battery to calculate a rough correction


When the battery starts, it only has the pack voltage, but not the individual cell voltages.

So as long as the cell voltage still has the default value 3.7 / 3.7 V for min/max, we will use:

pack voltage / 96

Once the min/max cell voltages are available, we will use them like this:

If pack voltage / 96 is higher than 3.8 V, we will use cellMax.
If it is lower than 3.8 V, we will use cellMin.

To this cell voltage, we will add the correction:

((R_mibha + 30) / 96 × I)

The value 30 should be implemented as a variable. It is another correction value that came out of real vehicle operation.

Then we will translate this corrected voltage using the table for the 60 / 94 / 120 Ah version, apply some damping so it does not move too quickly, and we will have SOC_Havrla.

In the battery settings, we will add an option:

Use SOC_Havrla.